PuppiesXY (study2children)

Adam Stone, PhD

04-21-2018

For now were just working with babies. So that means we need to pull baby info from cleanedbabyeyedata.feather. Below is a table of how many rows of data each baby has.

# Libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(feather)
library(lme4)
package lme4 was built under R version 3.4.4package Matrix was built under R version 3.4.4
library(lmerTest)
package lmerTest was built under R version 3.4.4
# Import data 
data <- read_feather("xypuppies.feather") %>%
  select(participant, condition, trial, x, y) %>%
  rename(name = participant)
# Pull baby names/info
babies <- read_feather("cleanedbabyeyedata.feather") %>%
  mutate(age = age*12) %>%
  select(participant, language, age) %>%
  rename(name = participant) %>%
  mutate(agegroup = case_when(
    age <= 8.99 ~ "younger",
    age >= 9.0 & age < 15 ~ "older"
  )) %>%
  filter(!is.na(agegroup)) %>%
  distinct()
package bindrcpp was built under R version 3.4.4
# Filter that with xypuppies data
data <- left_join(babies, data, by = "name")
data %>% count(name)

And lets get means per trial per baby.

data_stats <- data %>%
  group_by(name, age, language, condition, trial) %>%
  summarise(x = mean(x, na.rm=TRUE),
            y = mean(y, na.rm=TRUE))
data_stats

Lets visualize. Remember not all the puppy pictures are the same size, though.

ggplot(data_stats, aes(x = x, y = -1*y, color = language)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap("condition") + theme_linedraw() + xlab("mean x position") + ylab("mean y position")

And run a linear mixed model. First, x-axis - no differences of group (p = .52) or of age (p = .87) or interactions. Great!

lmm_x <- lmer(data = data_stats, x ~ language * age + (1|condition) + (1|name))
summary(lmm_x)

Next, y-axis - no NSE/SE differences (p = 0.82) but there is an effect of age (p = 0.03)!! Interesting.

Lets explore the effect of age on the y-axis some morethis tells us there IS an effect but its very subtle. And the LMM output above tells us that its about 4 pixels for every month. So a 12-month-old looks about 29 pixels lower compared to a 6-month-old. That is nothing, its not half of an AOI. Its a significant effect, but its a tiny thing and likely nothing to worry about. I think!!

ggplot(data_stats, aes(x = age, y = -1*y)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5, aes(color = language)) + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + facet_wrap("condition") + theme_linedraw() + ylab("mean y position") +
  xlab("age (months)")

Shifting 4 babies

How do results change if I shift 4 babies?

Now re-run the linear model for y-axis. The age effect is more significant (p = 0.005) and the magnitude is now 5.7 pixels per month. 12-month-olds look 34 pixels lower than 6-month-olds.
